"This is all the WAU, right? It's looking for anything, anything alive." Always thought Simon should have somehow destroyed the brain of the last living human. There's a bunch of WAU structure gel growths in her room already. What's to stop them from growing into her and reanimating her like those dudes on the bunks downstairs?
;
The dude that's got all the tentacles growing into him holding the picture of his kid is still semi-conscious too. It'd be a real horrorshow if the last living human went out thinking she could die in peace only to get pulled back in as another post-human monstrosity.

‚Äã¬†@assistantmagus5213¬† "because it was capturing scans of their brains when they used the pilot seats" Those are the Mockingbirds, like Catherine Mk3. I'm talking about the post-humans, the creatures formed from human bodies who are embedded in walls or independently active like discoball-head.
;
"Once you're dead your consciousness stops and you cease existing, the WAU cant bring you back" I'm not so sure that's true. The dude with the tentacles in him on the bed twitches and mumbles the name of his kid. So he still has some degree of motor function and memory. That seems more like he died but then the WAU reanimated him with brain damage.
;
Then there's the case of Johan Ross who died and was rebuilt by the WAU as a post-human but still retains full consciousness and will in his original body.

‚Äã¬†@Th3Sh1n1gam1¬† "so in the end... did humanity end because what we recognize as humans no longer exist? or did humanity actually overcome extinction if the Wau continued to exist and create its version of humanity." Personally I'd say humanity has ended as even the most sapient of the WAU's bunch, the Mockingbirds, generally don't regard each other as human. They regard each other as robots and even Catherine and Simon do so.
;
If there's to be a humanity then I think a basic requirement would be for most members of the species to recognize other members of the species.

